Trying to get a table at Brenda's is equivalent to getting tickets to see John Lennon in concert. He's dead. If you do happen to swipe a spot after a grueling 1.5 hr to 2 hr wait at the GATES DE BRENDA you will probably be so hungry that even a McDonald's chicken nugget would seem like a prize worthy piece of fried poultry. Okay maybe that is a tad harsh, Brenda's certainly has the atmosphere to swing you into a New Orleans Jazz frenzy, but if amazing soul food is what you are after then I recommend hiking over to Front Porch for the real deal (at a quarter of the wait time). I've been here a dozen of times, mostly because my Instagram whore friends can not get enough of posting square images of crawfish beignets cut in half and cheese grits closeups....and every time I leave wishing I was at Front Porch instead. Here is the lineup of the menu items I have had: Crawfish Beignets: despite my comment above, these were the saving grace. These beignets are incredible. Light, fluffy, salty, and perfectly spiced. When I eat these I want to wave my hands up in the air and scream Hallelujah while stomping my feet. I'm NOT over exaggerating. Shrimp and Grits: Super heavy. Greasy. Meh. One thing I HATE is when restaurants try and create flavor by just adding a shit ton of butter. Last I checked, this was not Paula Dean's restaurant. AND HOW THE HELL AM I SUPPOSED TO LOG THIS SHIT IN MY FITNESS PAL?! Fried Chicken: Pretty fuckin' good...but Front Porch is better. Good crunch, nice spice, but nothing to stomp my feet and cause a raucous about. The biscuit, is, however, YUMMY SCRUMBOS. Yeah, I said YUMMY SCRUMBOS...not let's move on. Fried Chicken Eggs Benedict: The hollandaise was WEIRD. It lacked spice. It lacked taste. It lacked a whole lot of something. Not a fan. SKIP if you know what is good for you. In addition to these items above, I've tried a whole slew of the dinner entrees but I was pretty drunk during the time and don't remember the exact flavor profiles...I will say that even in my blurriest of moments I can usually recall a good meal so this is not a good indicator. Needless to say, if you do happen to make it through and meet John Lennon at the entry way try the beignets...in a to go order as you uber over to Front Porch to enjoy the REAL BEST soul food spot in town.

Food: 5/5 Price: 5/5 Service: 5/5 Organization: 5/5 Layout: 5/5 Ambiance: 5/5 Honestly I haven't had much experience with soul food, but this was a great first impression. My friend took me here on my week long visit to SF and I couldn't wait to rave about this spot! It is in the shadier part of the city so taking a cab there or walking in a group may be recommended if you're visiting the city. The service and organizational flow are superb. They're not pushy but they are genuinely friendly and make you feel at home. The layout is charming with mirrors of all types hanging on the wall. I did mean to ask why there was a crack up the wall but it added to the atmosphere in my opinion. Plus the chalk sign in board was a nice touch. The ambiance was very relaxing and added to the mood. The music was not too loud and it had a lot of throwback R&B. Now onto the main part of the food! I AM IN LOVE! - Watermelon Tea ($2.75): This tea is a must have! It is nice and refreshing and really flavorful. There is just the right amount of blend to bring out the full tea and watermelon flavors without the excess water that some teas will leave you feeling. No sugar necessary to add. - Crawfish Beignets ($3.50 each): The beignets were nice and crispy on the outside and the inside was just marvelous! They are definitely a must have. If you do not like spicy, you have nothing to fear. The spice is very mild to say the least and just blends right into the overall taste. This was my first time ever having one and I am now hooked! - Casino Oysters ($2.75 each): The oysters were also superb. No complaints on that level at all. They were very soft and easily came apart from the shell. I also didn't taste any sand which quite often happens when I partake in shellfish. - Pork Shoulder ($16.75): This is a dish you will finish by yourself! The pork was just heavenly. It literally melted. Combined with the mashed potatoes and the green beans, it was a fantastic, yet simple combination. Coming from Hawaii where we have Kalua Pork, this really made me feel like I was having a cultural experience of soul food since we have our own flavor of soul food here in the islands. We were a bit too stuffed to fully indulge in dessert but the waitress was nice enough to allow us to purchase one of the Granny Smith Apple Beignets for $2.25. My friend got a little worried when I told him I was about to cry from the overall flavor. It was like biting into my grandma's apple pie. The outside was nice and crispy and reminded me of a malasada and the inside had a good amount of cinnamon for just the right blend. Overall, if you are visiting SF, please please please go and visit this place. You will not be disappointed! The oysters and dessert do have a sampler so you can have a little bit of everything.

The shrimp poboy was awesome. It's a classic french type of soul food. Heart. Ambiance of the venue was great. I wouldn't come with more than 5/6 people.

WOWWWWWWWWWWWWWWWWW When my friend and I visited SF and she told me we were going to visit Brenda's for some beignets, I wasn't all that interested. When you had the real thing in New Orleans, why bother with anything else? But since it's vacation, I decided to give it a try. First of all, they do NOT do reservations, so don't even try calling, especially on Sunday brunch time. Second, the lines are looooooooong. You walk inside and write your name down a la grade school style on the chalk board. And then you wait. And wait. (My suggestion is to hit up the cute little breakfast nook next door.) Finally our names were called and we got our seats. We ordered the 4 Beignets thinking there were the mini ones we had on Nawleans. Nope. Not even close. First there are as huge as your head and come in four different flavors: crawfish (surprisingly delicious!) plain, chocolate, and apple. They were sooo good but geeze, I wish someone would've warned us! By the time we got our meals I was well on my way to Sleepytown. I had the shrimp and goat cheese omelette with a biscuit and potato skins which were to die for. And I loved that they gave me a Mimosa but with agave juice (yum!). The staff is super friendly and I love the decor and music. Warning: Bring your fat pants. Don't eat for a solid 24 hours. Be prepared to be taken by Brenda and end up weeping in a corner over how she destroyed you...but you'll love it.

Food for the soul indeed. I was in SF for one day, and although I never eat breakfast, this restaurant intrigued me with its menu... so I woke up in time for breakfast and dragged my boyfriend with me. So happy I did. I was immediately impressed upon walking in. The decor was so... different! Like, in a good way. I guess from the outside, you don't really expect a contemporary type of place, but it was decorated nicely and had a friendly atmosphere. We both got the watermelon iced tea, which was definitely different from any other iced teas I've had. It was sooo refreshing! I loved it, I wish they have watermelon iced teas everywhere, because I would order it all the time. We also got the flight of beignets, which came with 4 different types - crawfish, apple, chocolate, and plain. This was my first time having beignets, and I enjoyed them a lot! I think the crawfish one was the best, probably because I was just craving savory foods at the time. But the other 3 were also good! Soft, fluffy, and slightly sweet. I ordered the grillades and grits, which came with grits, braised ribs, 2 eggs of your choice (mine was over-easy), and some toast. IT WAS SO GOOD. The grits were creamy, the braised ribs were tender and flavorful, and eating them all together = party in my mouth. My boyfriend got the egg and bacon tartine, which was good too, but I liked my order 10x more :) I was already halfway full from the beignets, but I wanted to finish my meal soooo bad... I couldn't do it. Neither could the bf. So we just got a to-go box and put whatever else we had left into it. A few hours later, on our drive back to LA, I finished it all and enjoyed it just the same, even though it was cold. That's how good it was. I'm coming back to SF in a week, and I really really want to come back here to try more things and their watermelon iced tea!!!

Cute soul food restaurant located in the Tenderloin of SF. When you first enter, there is a giant chalkboard for you to write your name and number of people in your party. We didn't get a chance to do that, though, since we were quickly seated! Service: Servers were polite, however, we were not checked on. We had to waive someone down for water, to put in our dessert order, and for the check. Food: - Shrimp and Grits - Despite all of the highly recommended reviews for the Shrimp and Grits, I really didn't see what all the hype was about. My boyfriend and I decided to split this, and even then, the portion was pretty large. I enjoyed the first few bites, but after a while, it was just too much...too rich, too cheesy, too oily. I would much prefer this as a side dish. - Catfish Po'boy Sandwich - SO glad I ordered this! Comes with fries, cole slaw, or both. I definitely recommend getting half and half!...They still give a generous portion of each. Fries were definitely way TOO salty. The texture of the fries were perfectly crispy yet soft in the center, but it would have been all the more enjoyable if they didn't drop the whole salt shaker on them. - Triple Chocolate Beignets - MUST SAVE ROOM FOR THESE. Enough powdered sugar on these babies that after one bite, you'll look like an addict...and after trying these, you might actually be addicted to them! They use Ghirardelli chocolate! Yum! Melted, but not completely so that some of the chocolate chips are still visible. An order gets you three of these delectable treats. Overall, Brenda's was fun to try once, but I think I will only come again if I happen to be in the area.

    WOWWWWWWWWWWWWWWWWW

    When my friend and I visited SF and she told me we were going to visit Brenda's for some beignets, I wasn't all that interested. When you had the real thing in New Orleans, why bother with anything else? But since it's vacation, I decided to give it a try.

    First of all, they do NOT do reservations, so don't even try calling, especially on Sunday brunch time. Second, the lines are looooooooong. You walk inside and write your name down a la grade school style on the chalk board. And then you wait. And wait. (My suggestion is to hit up the cute little breakfast nook next door.)

    Finally our names were called and we got our seats. We ordered the 4 Beignets thinking there were the mini ones we had on Nawleans. Nope. Not even close. First there are as huge as your head and come in four different flavors: crawfish (surprisingly delicious!) plain, chocolate, and apple. They were sooo good but geeze, I wish someone would've warned us!

    By the time we got our meals I was well on my way to Sleepytown. I had the shrimp and goat cheese omelette with a biscuit and potato skins which were to die for. And I loved that they gave me a Mimosa but with agave juice (yum!).

    The staff is super friendly and I love the decor and music. Warning: Bring your fat pants. Don't eat for a solid 24 hours. Be prepared to be taken by Brenda and end up weeping in a corner over how she destroyed you...but you'll love it.

    Food for the soul indeed. I was in SF for one day, and although I never eat breakfast, this restaurant intrigued me with its menu... so I woke up in time for breakfast and dragged my boyfriend with me. So happy I did.

    I was immediately impressed upon walking in. The decor was so... different! Like, in a good way. I guess from the outside, you don't really expect a contemporary type of place, but it was decorated nicely and had a friendly atmosphere. We both got the watermelon iced tea, which was definitely different from any other iced teas I've had. It was sooo refreshing! I loved it, I wish they have watermelon iced teas everywhere, because I would order it all the time.

    We also got the flight of beignets, which came with 4 different types - crawfish, apple, chocolate, and plain. This was my first time having beignets, and I enjoyed them a lot! I think the crawfish one was the best, probably because I was just craving savory foods at the time. But the other 3 were also good! Soft, fluffy, and slightly sweet.

    I ordered the grillades and grits, which came with grits, braised ribs, 2 eggs of your choice (mine was over-easy), and some toast. IT WAS SO GOOD. The grits were creamy, the braised ribs were tender and flavorful, and eating them all together = party in my mouth. My boyfriend got the egg and bacon tartine, which was good too, but I liked my order 10x more :) I was already halfway full from the beignets, but I wanted to finish my meal soooo bad... I couldn't do it. Neither could the bf. So we just got a to-go box and put whatever else we had left into it. A few hours later, on our drive back to LA, I finished it all and enjoyed it just the same, even though it was cold. That's how good it was. I'm coming back to SF in a week, and I really really want to come back here to try more things and their watermelon iced tea!!!

    1 check-in

    Cute soul food restaurant located in the Tenderloin of SF. When you first enter, there is a giant chalkboard for you to write your name and number of people in your party. We didn't get a chance to do that, though, since we were quickly seated!

    Service:
    Servers were polite, however, we were not checked on. We had to waive someone down for water, to put in our dessert order, and for the check.

    Food:
    - Shrimp and Grits - Despite all of the highly recommended reviews for the Shrimp and Grits, I really didn't see what all the hype was about. My boyfriend and I decided to split this, and even then, the portion was pretty large. I enjoyed the first few bites, but after a while, it was just too much...too rich, too cheesy, too oily. I would much prefer this as a side dish.
    - Catfish Po'boy Sandwich - SO glad I ordered this! Comes with fries, cole slaw, or both. I definitely recommend getting half and half!...They still give a generous portion of each. Fries were definitely way TOO salty. The texture of the fries were perfectly crispy yet soft in the center, but it would have been all the more enjoyable if they didn't drop the whole salt shaker on them.
    - Triple Chocolate Beignets - MUST SAVE ROOM FOR THESE. Enough powdered sugar on these babies that after one bite, you'll look like an addict...and after trying these, you might actually be addicted to them! They use Ghirardelli chocolate! Yum! Melted, but not completely so that some of the chocolate chips are still visible. An order gets you three of these delectable treats.

    Overall, Brenda's was fun to try once, but I think I will only come again if I happen to be in the area.

    Brenda's is a must if you are new to SF. Even if you're coming from NOLA, you'd like it.

    THE WAIT: There isnt usually that long of a wait (10-20 mins) as long as you avoid the obvious peak hours (20-30 min wait). when you walk in you sign up on a chalkboard and hang out until you're called. not a lot of indoor seating for waiting, but you can sit outside and bask in the San Francisco musk. If you are coming alone, there is a first come first serve bar on the side, usually no wait.

    THE FOOD: Awesome beignets, a dope as burger, shrimp, gumbo, and crawfish. The fried chicken isnt that great, but everything else i've had is!
